post_text:
For the 3rd year in a row, CH teams almost completely swept Utah's top spots in the eCybermission National STEM competition! All members of 2nd place teams receive a $500 savings bond, and all members of 1st place teams receive a $1000 savings bond. In addition, The Automators were regional finalists, which means they were among the top five teams in the western United States. They each receive an additional $1000 bond.

Approximately 5,000 teams across the U.S. participate in the competition.

GOOD MORNING Channing Hall Families! This week is kindness/anti-bullying week. Ms. Kaufusi and Ms. Tanner have put together some wonderful ideas for the week--today's theme is "I Can Make a Difference!"

Kindness makes you feel good. Researchers have found that thinking of others brings about lasting well-being. Kindness is contagious, and just as rewarding for the giver as the receiver.

Activity: Do as many acts of kindness as you can this week. They can be as simple as opening a door or calling or writing a letter to a loved one. Pick up trash on your daily walk, read with a sibling, or do an extra chore without being asked.

Fill out the Google Form with your acts of kindness!! We will make a list to share with Channing Hall students.
Acts of Kindness Google Form https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSepz9CFnO6NDnMtuO6R7u6Cle-jqqnWnGA8_8QW0X2M_SiFVg/viewform?fbclid=IwAR24CvTifevvbimUYV0KIQPklVwkM_yDFiIOGiT5AtZDzKcRRU64BcxaPYc

post_text:
Miss Missy had her students build their own Rube Goldberg Machines. Wow! Very creative and cool!

"A Rube Goldberg machine, named after American cartoonist Rube Goldberg, is a machine intentionally designed to perform a simple task in an indirect and overly complicated way. Usually, these machines consist of a series of simple unrelated devices; the action of each triggers the initiation of the next, eventually resulting in achieving a stated goal. The design of such a "machine" is often presented on paper and would be impossible to implement in actuality. More recently, such machines are being fully constructed for entertainment."

Check this one out. I know my dogs would love this!

Dear Parents,

Tomorrow morning we start eLearning. Our teachers and staff have been working tirelessly to get this rolling. I am so proud of them. Please help us by remembering that there will be kinks to work out. There will be glitches. It takes time to smooth these out. So tomorrow we appreciate your patience with us. We will be working throughout the day to help solve any issues. Thank you in advance for understanding. After a bit of time, things become easier for all. Teachers and administrators are available by email during school hours to help with classroom questions or problems. We want the very best for all of our students and their families.

Sincerely,
Diane

Yesterday the MYP teachers and I celebrated some of our students. We want to be more mindful about the power of recognition and the need to do more. We plan on doing this monthly, to remind our students how much we value their hard work, grit, problem solving, and being a great person., among other traits. We want them to celebrate their progress and the success and progress of their peers. Every student needs to hear this.
#OurMiddleSchoolersRock #MyMYPTeachersRock Proud to be a part of the team. We had one student absent, so I'll put his pic in next week.

post_text:
Thank you, thank you, thank you for your generous donations. As a school, we raised
$ 58,881.63, which was 84% of our goal. Your generosity is so greatly appreciated. This supports our classroom aides and tutors. Other funding priorities include possible changes in math curriculum, Scientist Suzie and science fair support, professional development for teachers and staff and a fund to provide financial assistance to students in need.
Channing Hall is an amazing school, and with this, our mission is to take our students and this school to the highest level possible. We can't do it without your partnership and we are grateful for your support.‚ù§Ô∏è
Sincerely,
Diane

post_text:
The art and skill of Tinikling.

Tinikling is a traditional Philippine folk dance which originated during the Spanish colonial era. The dance involves two people beating, tapping, and sliding bamboo poles on the ground and against each other in coordination with one or more dancers who step over and in between the poles in a dance.

Mrs. Tanner‚Äôs class has it down. I tried, but still have some learning to do.

post_text: Our sixth graders are having a great experience from the Loveland Living Aquarium. They are learning more about ecosystems and living things in the systems. Students are also learning about the impact of removal of animals in ecosystems. The armadillo is named Rose. Edgar is the Madagascar hissing cockroach. These cockroaches help keep the environment clean. He eats nature‚Äôs trash, not human trash. Yuki, a boa constrictor, also made her presence.

post_text:
Grandparents Day is October 8th during our Book Fair! We invite all grandparents and/or special friends to visit their student during lunch. Visitors may bring lunch in for their student or eat in the cafeteria. Cost for the school lunch for visitors is $3.00.

Lunch times:
Kindergarten: 11:50-12:15
1st Grade: 12:20-1:00
2nd Grade: 12:10-12:50
3rd Grade: 12:25-1:05
4th Grade: 12:00-12:40
5th Grade: 12:05-12:45
6-8th Grade: 12:55-1:20

Grandparents and Friends may eat with students, browse the book fair open during lunch and pose for a photo. Prints will be delivered to students the week of 10/14.

**Please park at Smith Field's Park if you are able. If an escort into the building is needed, please contact your student's teacher

Dear Parents,

There is a calendar change for October. Previously, students were to be out of school on Oct. 28th for teacher professional development. We are now holding the professional development on Friday, Nov. 1st, so students will not be in school on that day. That is the day after Halloween, so your children now will have that day off. Students are now to attend on Monday, Oct. 28th. As a reminder, we also have early dismissal on Thursday, Oct. 31st.

Please mark your calendar accordingly for these dates:
Oct. 28th-School is in session.
Oct. 31st-Halloween, early dismissal at 1:20.
Nov. 1st-Professional Development, No School.

Thank you for your support.

shared_text:
Draper City
June 12, 2019 at 8:59 AM ¬∑

At last night's City Council meeting, the Draper Mayor and City Council members recognized Channing Hall students who were named the Top Teams from the State of Utah in the eCybermission Science and Engineering Competition, sponsored by the U.S. Army.

The 6th, 7th and 8th grade teams all took 1st and 2nd place in their grade in the competition. In addition, Team Think Blue was selected as one of 20 teams in the nation to attend the national competition in Washington D.C. this June.

Their teachers are math and science educators Jenny McIntosh and Jeff Meyers.

Congratulations students for your hard work and creativity!

Draper City
June 12, 2019 at 8:59 AM ¬∑

At last night's City Council meeting, the Draper Mayor and City Council members recognized Channing Hall students who were named the Top Teams from the State of Utah in the eCybermission Science and Engineering Competition, sponsored by the U.S. Army.

The 6th, 7th and 8th grade teams all took 1st and 2nd place in their grade in the competition. In addition, Team Think Blue was selected as one of 20 teams in the nation to attend the national competition in Washington D.C. this June.

Their teachers are math and science educators Jenny McIntosh and Jeff Meyers.

Congratulations students for your hard work and creativity!

Here's an impressive tale: Nearly 200 students at Channing Hall read thousands of pages to compete in this week's Battle of the Books. Teams faced off to answer questions about 40 different novels in our own version of March Madness. We'll have an assembly the week after spring break to honor the winners. In the meantime, we are inspired to read a good book over the break. We hope you are too!

A huge round of applause for third grade teacher Kristin Brown for bringing Battle of the Books to our school. Everyone who participated won in this competition.

As an International Baccalaureate School we strive to develop students who will build a better world through understanding and respect. Today we demonstrated that very respect for those men and women of the armed forces who have protected our freedoms here in the United State of America.

We are so grateful for the fantastic musical presentations from our choir and students directed by Mr. Robertson as well as the heart-felt speech from Brandy Vega. We also express our appreciation to those who joined our celebration today!

We honor those ordinary people who have done something extraordinary so that we may all enjoy the freedom we treasure today.
